<H3> <TI>   Airbus A321 Receives JAA Certification </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WS0203C Paris AIR &amp; COSMOS/AVIATION MAGAZINE INTERNATIONAL 
in French 10-16 Jan 94 p 21--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WS0203C </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AIR &amp; COSMOS/AVIATION MAGAZINE INTERNATIONAL 
in French 10-16 Jan 94 p 21--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Article by Christel Tardif: "European Certification of the </F>
Airbus A321"--first paragraph is AIR &amp; COSMOS/AVIATION 
MAGAZINE 
INTERNATIONAL introduction] 
  [Text] Nine months after its first flight, the elongated 
version of the A320 equipped with V2500 engines is ready for its 
first delivery to Lufthansa, scheduled for 27 January. 
  The two A321 flight prototypes equipped with V2500 reactors 
supplied by International Aero Engines (IAE) had accumulated 605 
flight hours on 17 December 1993, when the aircraft was approved 
by the European certification authority (JAA). This paved the 
way for a first delivery to Lufthansa, the German airlines, next 
27 January. 
  The other two flight prototypes, equipped with CFM56-5B 
engines, already total 400 flight hours and are still being 
tested in Toulouse. This second A321 version should be approved 
by the JAA some time next March. JAA approval should occur 
simultaneously with that of U.S. certification authorities 
(FAA), for versions equipped with either engine. 
  Alitalia, who bought 40 A321 equipped with CFM engines 
should 
receive its first aircraft immediately after this certification, 
late in March. 
  The A321 is the elongated version of the A320, which means 
that it has a longer fuselage, as well as modified flaps and 
more powerful thrust engines (133.4 kilonewtons [kN] for the 
V2530-A5 engine, and 137.9 kN for the CFM56-5B2 engine, i.e. 
respectively 30,000 and 31,200 lbs of thrust). It also includes 
modifications enabling it to carry 185 passengers (or a maximum 
takeoff payload of 83 tons or 183,000 lbs) over up to 4,250 km 
(2,300 nautical miles) and at a cruising speed of up to Mach 
0.82, while benefiting from the experience of an aircraft that 
has been in service since 1988. 
  The Airbus Industrie backlog of orders includes 153 A321 
ordered so far by 11 clients. Deutsche Airbus, which makes them, 
has already assembled eight aircraft (including the four 
prototypes). 
<H5>  Production Authorization </H5>
  Simultaneously with the certification of the A321 IAE 
version, Airbus Industrie was just authorized to produce this 
entire aircraft line by French and German certification 
authorities (the DGAC [General Directorate of Civil Aviation] 
and the LBA [Germany's equivalent of the FAA]). This 
authorization will enable the consortium to complete on its own 
the compliance statement procedures for each unit produced in 
Toulouse or Hamburg. This obligation must be fulfilled before 
the certification authorities of the country of origin (in this 
case France and Germany) will issue the aircraft airworthiness 
certificate required for delivery. Until now, these procedures 
were completed by Bureau Veritas, a body approved by the DGAC. 

</TEXT>

