<H3> <TI>   ONERA Experiments With Supersonic Combustion </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94WS0203D Paris AIR &amp; COSMOS/AVIATION MAGAZINE INTERNATIONAL 
in French 10-16 Jan 94 p 22--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94WS0203D </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AIR &amp; COSMOS/AVIATION MAGAZINE INTERNATIONAL 
in French 10-16 Jan 94 p 22--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105>French </F>
Article Type:CSO 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Powder-Propellant Supersonic </F>
Combustion"] 
  [Text] ONERA [National Office for Aerospace Studies and 
Research] successfully tested a powder-propellant ramjet engine 
equipped with a plexiglass combustion chamber. A Mach 1.5 hot 
air flow was supplied to the chamber (consisting of a short 
cylindrical section followed by a divergent), and a small amount 
of hydrogen gas was injected into a mixed supersonic speed zone 
located at the chamber inlet (this to help maintain combustion). 
Typical speeds at the chamber outlet ranged from Mach 1.1 to 
Mach 1.4, and combustion efficiencies observed were as high as 
87 percent, with equivalence ratios ranging from 0.49 to 0.66. 
In the present setup, however, losses due to the calorific 
intake and to friction against the walls resulted in a 50-70 
percent impact pressure drop throughout the chamber. 

</TEXT>

