<ABS>  Japan </ABS>
<DATE1>   31 February 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> Science &amp; Technology Policy/Economic Competitiveness </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI To Formulate Technology Vision for Small, Mid-Sized Enterprises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  93FE0811A Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 29 Jun 93 p 
1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 93FE0811A </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIKKAN KOGYO SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] The Small and Medium Enterprise Agency of the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) is designing 
a new vision for the 21st century for technology policies for 
small- and medium-sized businesses. The Technology Policy 
Committee to be established as a part of the Small and Medium 
Sized Enterprise Modernization Council (an advisory organ of the 
Minister of MITI) will begin deliberations this fall. While 
developing a successor law to the Law on Extraordinary Measures 
for the Technology Development Promotion for Small and Medium 
Enterprises, which will expire at the deadline of July 1995, the 
Council will carry out support for restructuring and find uses 
of regional public research institutes (kohsetsushi labs) by 
regional industries. 
  Almost 10 years have passed since the Small and Medium 
Enterprise Agency endeavored to devise a new vision for 
technology policy based on a report completed in February 1985 
by committee of the Small and Medium Sized Enterprise 
Modernization Council. This committee recognized the need for 
new objectives given the changing economic and technological 
environments. 
  The Law on Extraordinary Measures for the Technology 
Development Promotion for Small and Medium Enterprises which 
currently forms the basis for technology policies for small- and 
medium-sized enterprises is based on the 1985 report. Support 
policies like loans for advanced capital, tax reduction 
measures, and exceptions for extra credit for companies 
implementing development plans authorized by the prefecture are 
organized under this law. Since this law has a 10-year limit, 
this system will discontinue as of July 1995. 
  The purpose of the new vision is to design a successor law. 
The report of the Basic Policy Study Group of the Small and 
Medium Enterprises Policy Council sought clarification of the 
vision for technology policy for the country. To address this, a 
study will begin. The Technology Policy Committee to be 
established this fall in the Small and Medium Enterprise 
Modernization Council will try to respond before the end of 
fiscal year 1993. 
  In concert with the new vision, about 170 kohsetsushi in 
prefectures throughout the country will begin to develop a 
system to facilitate the activities of small- and medium-sized 
enterprises like local manufacturing industries. Support for 
restructuring will also be included. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

