<F P=100> Nuclear Engineering </F>
<H3> <TI>   Atomic Energy Commission of Japan Decides Total Ban of Ocean Dumping of Low Level Waste </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  94FE0170C Tokyo KAGAKU KOGYO NIPPO in Japanese 4 Nov 93 p 12 
--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> 94FE0170C </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KAGAKU KOGYO NIPPO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:CSO 

  [Text] On 2 November, the Atomic Energy Commission of Japan 
(JAEC; chaired by Science and Technology Agency (STA) Director 
General Satsuki Eda) decided to change the existing policy of 
disposing of low level radioactive waste from nuclear power 
plants basically by burial underground or ocean dumping so that 
the latter, ocean dumping, will not be used in the future. This 
measure was taken out of consideration for the fact that ocean 
dumping of radioactive waste by Russia has rapidly strengthened 
sentiment for a total ban on ocean dumping. 
  The government has expressed the plan to vote in favor of a 
total ban on ocean dumping at a conference of London Treaty 
signatories, which will convene in London on 8 November, and the 
JAEC's decision confirms this. STA says that ``this will not 
affect Japan's nuclear energy policy immediately'' because Japan 
is not dumping in the ocean at this time. 
  The JAEC maintains that ocean dumping of low level 
radioactive nuclear waste has no special effect on public health 
according to International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
standards. However, judging from the Japanese and international 
reaction to ocean dumping by Russia, it believes that ``from a 
political and social viewpoint, it would be extremely difficult 
to carry out ocean dumping.'' It says that hereafter, 
``underground burial will be used,'' and it is seeking to expand 
those facilities. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

